article.description: Antawn Jamison scored 20 points, capped by a putback with 4.9 seconds remaining that led the Dallas Mavericks to an 81-78 victory win over San Antonio on Saturday night.
article.headline: Jamison's follow lifts Mavs to win
article.linkText: A shot of Jamison spurs Dallas over San Antonio
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Antawn Jamison came off the bench and beat the San Antonio Spurs inside. Jamison scored 20 points, capped by a 1-foot putback with 4.9 seconds remaining, that led the Dallas Mavericks to an 81-78 victory over the Spurs on Saturday night. "I just run the floor and try to hit the glass," said Jamison, who turned three of his four offensive rebounds into close-in scores. "Some guys are going to have to do some dirty work." For San Antonio, most of the dirty work was done by Malik Rose, who paced the Spurs with 20 points and a career-high 22 rebounds, but still felt dejected afterward. "It's another frustrating night," said Rose, whose team slipped to 3-4 with the loss. "We played hard as always and competed but it's just discouraging to lose another game." The Spurs played without Tim Duncan, who has a sprained left ankle, for the third straight game. Point guard Tony Parker, who also has a sprained left ankle, is yet to play this season. San Antonio, which trailed for most of the game, went up 78-77 on a corner 3-pointer by Bruce Bowen with 1:29 left. But Steve Nash made a jumper on the next possession to put the Mavericks back on top. "That's the fun part about playing sometimes -- when you get a shot that really makes the difference between winning and losing," said Nash, who sat out the Mavs' loss Thursday in Toronto with a left shoulder strain. Michael Finley stole the ball from Rose with 50.9 seconds left and then grabbed the rebound of an errant 3-point shot by Antoine Walker with 29 seconds left. Nash missed on a drive to the basket, but Jamison, who finished with nine rebounds, was there for the putback. On San Antonio's final chance, Robert Horry was way long on a 3-point attempt. Nash finished with 15 points. Dirk Nowitzki also had 15 and Tony Delk 12. Manu Ginobili scored 17 points for the Spurs and Rasho Nesterovic added 10. San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said he's impressed with his team's tenacity while playing without its two injured stars. On Thursday the Spurs took the healthy Los Angeles Lakers to double overtime before losing. "I hope that when Tim and Tony come back, we still play as well," Popovich said. A 12-0 run by Dallas in the first period gave the Mavericks an early lead. The Spurs missed nine of their first 10 shots. While San Antonio's shooters continued to struggle, the Mavericks kept pushing the ball in transition for easy inside baskets. Dallas scored 48 of its 81 points in the paint. Dallas stretched its lead to 52-38 on a running jumper by Eduardo Najera with 1:12 left in the half before a layup by Horry and four foul shots cut the deficit to 53-44 at the break. After Nowitzki made a 16-footer to open the third quarter, San Antonio went on a 15-4 run ending with a 3-pointer by Ginobili to go up 59-57 midway through the period.

Game notes
San Antonio placed guard Ron Mercer (inflamed left ankle) on the injured list before the game and activated guard Devin Brown, who had two points in six minutes. ... On Monday, the Spurs host Utah, whom they have defeated 13 straight times. That game will also feature a ceremony to retire David Robinson's No. 50 jersey. ... The Mavericks made only 11 of 43 3-point attempts (25.6 percent) in their last three games. ... Dallas is now 2-3 on the road. The Mavs host New Orleans on Tuesday.
